{"key":"post-12397750","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12397750</id>\n<content>Cracked corn leaks a lot of starch out, which will lead to a higher incidence of uncolonized areas, thus more contamination.&amp;nbsp; Even popcorn generally has many more bacterial endospores than other grains, leading to a higher rate of bacterial contamination.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The 'faster colonization' you see is related to the fact that the mycelium initially only colonizes the surface of the grains, thus a grain with a large surface area seems to colonize faster, but in a given sized jar, you only have a third or less the amount of mycelium you'd have with a smaller grain.&amp;nbsp; In other words, large grains such as corn are inferior when spawned to a bulk substrate.&amp;nbsp; Corn was all the rage a few years ago until people discovered that they can get a higher success ratio with other grains, such as rye berries, which is best.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12410673</next>\n<prev>12397711</prev>\n<first>12085159</first>\n<last>12410731</last>\n<when>1271351840</when>\n<utime>04/15/10 08:17 PM</utime>\n</post>"}